content.text:
I see the issue. In your `.card` grid (line 197-218), you're using `grid-area: 1 / 1` to stack `.title` and `.graphic` on top of each other. The `.graphic` class is on the `<img>` inside `<picture>`, but the `<picture>` element is the actual grid child — not the `<img>`.

The fix is to either:

1. **Style the `<picture>` as the grid item** and keep the `<img>` styling for object-fit:

```css
.card {
  background: silver;
  display: grid;
  flex: 1;

  .title,
  picture {
    grid-area: 1 / 1;
  }

  .graphic {
    display: block;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
    height: 100%;
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

2. **Or** add `display: contents` to `<picture>` so it becomes invisible to the grid and the `<img>` becomes the direct grid participant:

```css
picture {
  display: contents;
}
```

Option 1 is more explicit and predictable. The grid placement goes on `picture` (the actual grid child), and the `object-fit` stuff stays on the `<img>` via `.graphic`. Want me to make that change?

The problem is that `.graphic` (the `<img>` inside `<picture>`) is **not** a direct child of the `.card` grid. The grid children are:

1. `img.title` — direct child, `grid-area: 1 / 1` works
2. `<picture>` — direct child, but has **no** grid placement

Since `.graphic` is nested inside `<picture>`, its `grid-area: 1 / 1` declaration does nothing for grid layout. The `<picture>` element gets auto-placed into row 2, so you end up with two rows instead of a stack:

- Row 1: the title logo (267×227)
- Row 2: the picture element

They're not overlapping at all. As the card widens, the two-row layout becomes more apparent and the title sits above the image rather than on top of it, which looks like it's pushing out.

The fix is to put the grid placement on `picture` (the actual grid child):

```css
.card {
  background: silver;
  display: grid;
  flex: 1;

  .title,
  picture {
    grid-area: 1 / 1;
  }

  .title {
    z-index: 2;
  }

  .graphic {
    display: block;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
    height: 100%;
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

This stacks `picture` and `.title` in the same cell. The `<picture>` stretches to fill the cell (default grid item behavior), and the inner `.graphic` img fills it with `object-fit: cover`. Want me to make this edit?

